    Formally infracast reference`
    - in form, a relative reference without a dot segment
        ( relative reference, https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986#section-4.2
        ( dot-segment,        https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986#section-3.3
    - it is intended for resolution in waycast context
        ( http://reluk.ca/project/wayic/cast/waycast_context
    - specifying it in a formal definition implies such resolution
        ( each actual reference will be so resolved
    - given this, a processor need perform no further bounds checking on actual references of this type
        - their form is self constrained to the waycast boundary
        - itself proof against an extracast referent
        ( e.g. as per § Design constraints § relative referencing bound by the waycast
    - hence references of this type are *formally* intracast

