    Offset capable referencing`
    - the use of an *offset* attribute (optional) and a refinement attribute (mandatory)
      to refer to an element regardless of whether it has an *id* attribute
    - offset mode (actual use of the *offset* attribute) is limited to wayscript referents
        ( § offset mode
    + *offset* attribution
        < way:offest, namespace data:,wayscript
        - attribute optional, the attribute itself may be omitted
            * not yet supported by wayic.read
                =wayic.read § *offset* attribution
                    ( http://reluk.ca/project/wayic/read/project.task
        - form
            - a fragmented, (§) formally infracast reference
            - infracast in compliance with design constraints
                ( § Design constraints § relative referencing bound by the waycast
        - function
            * function when omitted
                - switches the refinement attribute into identity mode
            * function when present
                - sets a context node for the reference
                    ( https://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-3/#id-relative-path-expressions
                - switches the refinement attribute into offset mode
    + refinement attribution
        - attribute mandatory, the attribute itself is always present
        - refinement attribution comprises:
            * formal attribute
                - the formal attribute given (named) to carry the refinement function
                < mandatory
            * URI referential constraint
                - a formal constraint given to define a *constrained URI reference*, q.v. below
                < optional
                    - it may be omitted, in which case the definition defaults to just a URI reference
                        ( URI reference, https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986#section-4.1
        - form
            < to the given (§) formal attribute
            - according to one of two formal modes as determined by the switching function
              of the *offset* attribution
            * offset mode
                - *offset* present: this mode occurs when the *offset* sibling attribute is present
                - an XPath relative path expression
                    ( https://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-3/#id-relative-path-expressions
                    - relative to the context node as set by the *offset* attribution
                    - enabling reference to an element absent an *id* attribute
            * identity mode
                - *offset* absent: this mode occurs when the *offset* sibling attribute is absent
                - a constrained URI reference
                    - from the given § URI referential constraint
                    - enabling reference to an element that presents an *id* attribute
        - function: refines the reference down to the precise location of the referent waybit

